'''Vincenzo Montella''' {{postnominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Cavaliere OMRI]]}} ({{IPA|it|vinˈtʃɛntso monˈtɛlla}}; born 18 June 1974) is an Italian [[association football|football]] manager and former [[striker (association football)|striker]]. He is the current head coach of the [[Turkey national football team]].

Montella's nickname during his playing career was "Aeroplanino", in reference to his small stature and trademark [[goal celebration]], in which he spread his arms like wings.<ref name="best nicknames">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=2045764.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129140314/http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=2045764.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=29 January 2014|title=European football's best nicknames|publisher=UEFA|date=27 January 2014|access-date=18 June 2017}}</ref> A prolific goalscorer,<ref name="Montella comes to the fore">{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/italy/newsid_1931000/1931746.stm|title=Montella comes to the fore|work=BBC Sport|author1=Dimitri Canello|date=15 April 2002|access-date=18 February 2017}}</ref><ref name="Euro 2000">{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/italy/squad/774717.stm|title=Player Profile|publisher=BBC|access-date=27 June 2012|date=15 June 2000}}</ref><ref name="UEFA">{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0241-0e77352cfc79-2c33e6310ca8-1000--vincenzo-montella/|title=Vincenzo Montella|publisher=[[UEFA]]|access-date=22 February 2017}}</ref><ref name="ritorno">{{cite web|url=http://it.eurosport.com/calcio/serie-a/2006-2007/montella-il-ritorno_sto1248182/story.shtml|title=Montella, il ritorno|date=16 July 2007|publisher=Eurosport|language=it|access-date=22 February 2017}}</ref><ref name="espn">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/euro2000/italy/player/Montella.html|title=Vincenzo Montella Profile|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Mark Thompson|date=13 July 2000|access-date=22 February 2017}}</ref> throughout his playing career Montella played as a [[forward (association football)|forward]] for Italian clubs [[Empoli FC|Empoli]], [[Genoa CFC|Genoa]], [[UC Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] and [[AS Roma|Roma]], and also had a spell on loan in England with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]. He is mostly remembered for his performances with Roma (1999–2007), where he won the [[Serie A]] title and the [[2001 Supercoppa Italiana|Supercoppa Italiana]] during the [[2000–01 Serie A|2000–01 season]], also later reaching the [[2003 Coppa Italia Final|2003 Coppa Italia final]] with the club. In 2013, Montella was inducted into the [[AS Roma Hall of Fame|Roma Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asroma.it/en/team/hall_of_fame.html|title=Hall of Fame 2014: Ghiggia, Ancelotti, Voeller and Candela inducted|publisher=AS Roma|access-date=10 February 2015|archive-date=19 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219121511/http://www.asroma.it/en/team/hall_of_fame.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> At international level, he made 20 appearances for [[Italian national football team|Italy]] between 1999 and 2005, scoring three goals; he was notably a member of the Italian team that reached the final of [[UEFA Euro 2000]], and he also represented his country at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].

Montella began his managerial career as Roma's caretaker manager in 2011, later coaching [[Catania calcio|Catania]] the following season. In 2012, he moved to [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], where he spent three seasons, leading the club to three consecutive fourth-place league finishes, the [[2014 Coppa Italia Final|2014 Coppa Italia final]] and the [[UEFA Europa League]] semi-finals in [[2014–15 UEFA Europa League|2015]]. After a season-long spell with Sampdoria, he was appointed Milan's manager in 2016, and later that year, he won his first title as a coach with the club, the [[2016 Supercoppa Italiana|Supercoppa Italiana]]. He was sacked by the club in 2017, and was subsequently appointed manager of Spanish side [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]. Despite reaching the [[2018 Copa del Rey Final|Copa del Rey final]] and reaching the Champions League quarter-finals for the first time in the club's history, he was sacked by Sevilla four months after his appointment, following a run that included nine matches without a victory. He returned to Fiorentina in 2019, with the second spell lasting over eight months.

After a period managing [[Adana Demirspor]] in the Turkish league, he was appointed as coach of the Turkish national team in September 2023, helping the team to qualify for [[UEFA Euro 2024]] and reach the quarter-finals, and also guided them to the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], marking their first appearance at the finals since 2002. Additionally, under his leadership, the team was promoted to [[2026–27 UEFA Nations League A|League A]], the top tier of the [[UEFA Nations League]], for the first time in its history in 2025.

==Club career==
===Early career===
Montella began his club career in [[Serie C1]] at [[Empoli FC|Empoli]] in 1990 before moving to [[Serie B]] club [[Genoa CFC|Genoa]] in 1995, where he scored 21 goals in his only season with the club, at the end of which he lifted the [[1995–96 Anglo-Italian Cup|Anglo-Italian Cup]]. He then moved up to [[Serie A]] to [[Derby della Lanterna|city rivals]] [[UC Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], where he remained three years, until 1999. After Sampdoria's relegation, he moved to Roma in a 50&nbsp;billion [[Italian lira|lire]] (about €25.823&nbsp;million) transfer.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.borsaitaliana.it/bitApp/view.bit?lang=it&target=DocViewerDownload&filename=db%2Fpdf%2F1094.pdf| title =BILANCIO D'ESERCIZIO E CONSOLIDATO DI GRUPPO AL 30 GIUGNO 2000 | date = 28 June 2001| language = it | access-date =24 March 2015 |work=AS Roma| publisher=Borsa Italiana Archive}}</ref>

Montella made his Serie A debut on 8 September 1996, against [[Perugia Calcio|Perugia]].

===Roma===
It was Roma coach [[Zdeněk Zeman]] that wanted him to spearhead the Roma attack, but that year Roma also signed a new coach, [[Fabio Capello]], who disliked short forwards. Despite this, during the [[1999–2000 Serie A|1999–2000 season]], Montella scored 18 goals, being the top scorer of the ''giallorossi'', playing alongside [[Marco Delvecchio]], in front of advanced playmaker [[Francesco Totti]]. The following year, Roma signed the Argentinian forward [[Gabriel Batistuta]] from [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], the tall striker wanted by Capello.

There was a slight controversy between the two forwards concerning the [[Squad number (association football)|number 9 shirt]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200008/22/39a2be7206b19/|title=A Montella il n. 9|publisher=Rai Sport|website=raisport.rai.it|language=it|access-date=17 December 2015|archive-date=3 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003181828/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200008/22/39a2be7206b19/|url-status=dead}}</ref> the prior number of both players – Batistuta ultimately chose number 18, although Batistuta was often the coach's first choice, while Montella was usually deployed as a substitute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200002/08/38a06eeb01113/|title=Il silenzio degli innocenti|website=raisport.rai.it|publisher=Rai Sport|language=it|access-date=17 December 2015|archive-date=3 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003181806/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200002/08/38a06eeb01113/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite his lack of starts, he was one of the main protagonists of Roma's third ''[[Scudetto]]'' in [[2000–01 Serie A|2000–01]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sport.sky.it/calcio/serie-a/fotogallery/2017/06/17/accadde-oggi-la-roma-vince-terzo-scudetto.html |title=17 giugno 2001: e Roma impazzì per lo scudetto |publisher=sport.sky.it |language=it |date=17 June 2017 |access-date=11 October 2019 }}</ref> and scored many important goals for the club, including the equalising goal in a 2–2 away draw in Serie A against eventual runners-up Juventus on 6 May 2001,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato_partite/juveroma/juveroma/juveroma.html|title=Montella e Nakata rimontano la Juve|work=La Repubblica.it|language=it|access-date=17 December 2015}}</ref> and Roma's second goal in the 3–1 title-deciding victory over [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] on 17 June, at the [[Stadio Olimpico]] in Rome.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato_partite/romaparma/romaparma/romaparma.html|title=Roma, show all'Olimpico per la festa scudetto|work=la Repubblica|language=it|date=17 June 2011|access-date=29 July 2016}}</ref>

The controversies between Capello and Montella continued in the following years, as Montella was unhappy at his lack of first team opportunities, and in March 2002, Montella made his sadness clear, stating: "I would have better expectations with another coach."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/ferrazza/ferrazza/ferrazza.html|title=Roma, Capello-Montella è lite continua|work=La Repubblica.it|language=it|access-date=17 December 2015}}</ref> Despite his struggle to gain a starting spot, he became a club idol to the supporters, as he had a knack for performing well in the [[Rome derby]] against [[SS Lazio|Lazio]], scoring a brace in his first derby in 1999, and four goals in a 5–1 win on 10 March 2002;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avvelenata.it/giallorossi/2001-02/lazioroma.html|title=Roma – Lazio 5–1|website=Avvelenata.it|language=it|access-date=17 December 2015}}</ref> this four-goal haul is still the record of goals scored in a derby match by a single player.

2003 was a difficult year for Montella, as he divorced from his former wife, Rita,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news2000.libero.it/gossip/wmr21.html|title=Un calcio al matrimonio|work=News2000.libero.it|language=it|access-date=17 December 2015}}</ref> and was plagued with many injuries. During the [[2003–04 Serie A|2003–04 season]], he played only twelve games, but still managed a solid scoring record, scoring six goals despite his limited playing time.

During the [[2004–05 Serie A|2004–05 season]], Capello finally left Roma – for [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] – and, while the ''giallorossi'' had a disastrous season, Montella scored 23 goals and earned a new contract lasting until 30 June 2010, also helping Roma to the [[2005 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia final]] that season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=295172.html|title=Montella rewarded by Roma|publisher=UEFA|date=13 April 2005|access-date=4 December 2013}}</ref> In the [[2005–06 Serie A|2005–06 season]], he was again plagued with injuries. He underwent surgery on both his back and shoulder, limiting him to just twelve games. In January 2007, during the [[2006–07 Serie A|2006–07 season]], he was loaned to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] because [[Francesco Totti]] was the lone forward in new head coach [[Luciano Spalletti]]'s [[Formation (association football)#4–2–3–1|4–2–3–1 formation]], while Montella wanted to have more chances to play.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Roma/Primo_Piano/2006/12_Dicembre/01/cec.shtml|title=Spalletti dà il via libera a Montella|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=it|date=1 December 2006|access-date=17 December 2015}}.</ref>

With Roma, Montella played a total of 215 matches over eight years, scoring 94 goals to become the [[AS Roma statistics#Top 15 all-time goalscorers|fifth-best topscorer in Roma history]]. He played his last game for Roma, on 23 December 2006, before leaving on loan to England.

====Loan to Fulham====
Montella joined Fulham on a six-month loan on 4 January 2007, and was given the number 11 shirt. He scored twice against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on his home debut, in the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/6258849.stm
|title=Fulham 4–3 Leicester
|publisher=BBC
|date=17 January 2007 |access-date=2 September 2009
|first=Paul
|last=Fletcher}}</ref> He scored again on 27 January in the same competition against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/6282173.stm
|title=Fulham 3–0 Stoke
|publisher=BBC
|date=27 January 2007 |access-date=2 September 2009
|first=Ian
|last=Hughes}}</ref>

On 13 January 2007, Montella made his [[Premier League]] debut, against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref name="Tactical Formation">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-lineups.com/match/3158/|title=Tactical Formation|work=Football-Lineups.com|access-date=4 December 2013}}</ref> Against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[Craven Cottage]] seven days later, he scored his first Premier League goal with a penalty kick.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/6258671.stm|title=Fulham 1–1 Tottenham|publisher=BBC|date=20 January 2007|access-date=2 September 2009}}</ref> He also scored a goal against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in a 1–1  draw, which gave Fulham the boost to avoid relegation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/6555243.stm|title=Fulham 1–1 Blackburn|publisher=BBC|first=Owen|last=Phillips|date=21 April 2007|access-date=2 September 2009}}</ref>

Montella quickly became popular with the Fulham fans, and showed his gratitude for making him feel at home at Craven Cottage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2007/january/22/high-flyer|title=High Flyer|work=FulhamFC.com|access-date=4 December 2013}}</ref> However, he hardly started under manager Chris Coleman, despite several public pleas.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11681/2409484/|title=MONTELLA MAKES COLEMAN PLEA|work=Sky Sports|access-date=27 March 2007}}</ref> After [[Chris Coleman (footballer)|Coleman]]'s sacking, Montella only started twice under his replacement [[Lawrie Sanchez]].<ref name="Tactical Formation"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.skysports.com/matchreport.aspx?fxid=298651&CPID=8&channel= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070622014850/http://home.skysports.com/matchreport.aspx?fxid=298651&CPID=8&channel=|archive-date=22 June 2007 |title=HUNT PILES PRESSURE ON FULHAM | first=James | last=Pearson |publisher=Sky Sports|date=14 April 2007|access-date=4 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fulham v Blackburn - 21st Apr 2007|work=Sky Sports | url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/83521 | access-date=4 December 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://home.skysports.com/matchreport.aspx?fxid=318294&CPID=8&channel= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709120738/http://home.skysports.com/matchreport.aspx?fxid=318294&CPID=8&channel=|archive-date=9 July 2007 |title=GUNNERS PILE PRESSURE ON FULHAM | first=Lewis | last=Rutledge  |publisher=Sky Sports|date=29 April 2007|access-date=4 December 2013}}</ref> Montella hinted that he would like to return to Roma, after the end of the 2006–07 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=MONTELLA EYES ROMA RETURN|work=Sky Sports |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11681/2412357/ | access-date= 4 December 2013 }}</ref> The loan was terminated by Sanchez on 8 May 2007, a week before its natural expiration.<ref>{{cite web|title=New boss Sanchez shows his teeth|work=Evening Standard |date=13 April 2012 |location=London|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/new-boss-sanchez-shows-his-teeth-6580951.html| access-date=4 December 2013}}</ref>

====Loan to Sampdoria and return====
He was loaned to Sampdoria for the [[2007–08 Serie A|2007–08 season]]. [[Bruno Conti]] brought Montella back to Roma in [[2008–09 AS Roma season|2008–09]], after [[Mancini (Brazilian footballer)|Mancini]] had departed Roma to join [[Inter Milan]]. Montella took number 23 when he came back; [[Mirko Vučinić]] held on the number 9 shirt which was formerly Montella's, and Montella took the number 23 shirt, formerly of Vučinić.

Montella was only able to make substitute appearances for Roma in the [[2008–09 Serie A|2008–09 season]]. He played his last game on 16 May 2009.

On 2 July 2009, Montella announced his retirement from professional football.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asroma.it/NewsDoc.aspx?Categoria=ITArchivioNews&Documento=10417|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705164931/http://www.asroma.it/NewsDoc.aspx?Categoria=ITArchivioNews&Documento=10417|archive-date=5 July 2009 |title=Grazie Vincenzo|publisher=asroma.it.|date=2 July 2009|access-date=4 December 2013|language=it}}</ref>

==International career==
Montella received his first international [[Cap (sport)|cap]] for [[Italy national football team|Italy]] under [[Dino Zoff]] in a [[UEFA Euro 2000 qualifying]] match against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] on 5 June 1999, which Italy won 4–0, coming on as a second-half substitute for [[Christian Vieri]];<ref name="treccani2"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/nazionale/199906/05/375982350400d/ |title=L'Italia si fa in quattro |publisher=RaiSport |language=it |date=5 June 1999 |access-date=3 October 2018 |archive-date=2 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202001529/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/nazionale/199906/05/375982350400d/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> he was part of the final 22-man Italian squad that took part at [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]], where they reached the [[UEFA Euro 2000 Final|final]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/4746336/Italy-Team-Details.html|title=Italy Team Details|newspaper=The Telegraph|author1=John Ley|date=9 June 2000|access-date=18 May 2015}}</ref> Although Montella did not score during the competition, he recorded an assist in Italy's final group match against [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]], setting up [[Alessandro Del Piero]]'s match-winning goal in the 2–1 victory, which allowed Italy to top their group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2000/round=1458/match=64856/report=rp.html|title=Italy foil brave Sweden|publisher=UEFA|access-date=18 May 2015|date=6 October 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110070652/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2000/round=1458/match=64856/report=rp.html|archive-date=10 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He would also make one more appearance during the tournament, in the 2–1 final defeat against [[France national football team|France]], coming on as a late second-half substitute for Roma teammate and goalscorer Marco Delvecchio, with Italy leading 1–0; France equalised in injury time and eventually won the match in extra-time courtesy of a [[David Trezeguet]] golden goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2000/round=1461/match=65299/report=rp.html|title=Trezeguet's golden moment|publisher=UEFA|date=6 October 2003|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110070653/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2000/round=1461/match=65299/report=rp.html|archive-date=10 January 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Italy in an international friendly match against [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] in [[Perugia]] on 25 April 2001, a 1–0 home win for Italy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/sport/itatrieste/sudafrica/sudafrica.html|title=La Nazionale supera il test del Sudafrica|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=it|access-date=21 September 2014}}</ref> On 27 March 2002, he scored a notable double against [[England national football team|England]] in an international friendly match in [[Leeds]], giving Italy a 2–1 away victory after they had been trailing 1–0, with his second, match-winning goal coming from an injury-time penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://storiedicalcio.altervista.org/02_mondiali_calcio_2002.html|title=Mondiale 2002 (Campione: Brasil) Capitolo II: L'Italia del Trap|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=it|access-date=21 September 2014|archive-date=13 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813074821/http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/02_mondiali_calcio_2002.html|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/mar/28/worldcupfootball2002.sport |title=Eriksson's team of two halves pay for their lapse at the last |newspaper=The Guardian |first=David |last=Lacey |date=28 March 2002 |access-date=3 October 2018 }}</ref>

After appearing for Italy under [[Giovanni Trapattoni]] during their [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2002 FIFA World Cup qualifying]] campaign, Montella was chosen as a member of the Italy team that would be competing at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], where the Italians were eliminated controversially in the round of 16 to co-hosts [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]], following a 2–1 defeat in extra time.<ref name="La storia dei Mondiali - 2002">{{cite web|url=https://it.eurosport.yahoo.com/02062010/45/storia-dei-mondiali-2002-mondiale-delle-sorprese-mancate.html|title=La storia dei Mondiali - 2002, Il Mondiale delle sorprese mancate|publisher=Eurosport|language=it|access-date=21 September 2014}}</ref><ref name="flop">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3029599/Italy-flop-as-Ahns-golden-goal-atones-for-penalty-miss.html|title=Italy flop as Ahn's golden goal atones for penalty miss|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=18 June 2002|access-date=26 May 2012}}</ref><ref name="Korea 2–1 Italy">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/jun/18/minutebyminute.worldcupfootball20021|title=South Korea 2–1 Italy – as it happened|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 June 2002|access-date=26 May 2012}}</ref> In his only [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] appearance, during Italy's final group stage match against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the 2002 World Cup, he had a goal disallowed. He later set up Del Piero's equaliser in the eventual 1–1 draw, which helped Italy to progress to the second round.<ref name="La storia dei Mondiali - 2002"/><ref name="Gruppo G: Italia-Messico 1-1">{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/diretta/online/italiamessico/|title=Gruppo G: Italia-Messico 1–1|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=it|access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> He had warmed up and was ready to come off the bench in the round of 16 match, but South Korea's [[Ahn Jung-hwan|Ahn]] scored the golden goal moments before he was set to come on.<ref name="La storia dei Mondiali - 2002"/><ref name="flop"/><ref name="Korea 2–1 Italy"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/diretta/online/coreita/index.html |title=Corea del Sud-Italia 2-1 |newspaper=La Repubblica |language=it |author1=MATTEO TONELLI |date=18 June 2002 |access-date=3 October 2018 }}</ref> He later also appeared for Italy in three [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying|Euro 2004 qualifying]] matches, but was not called up for the [[UEFA Euro 2004|final tournament]]. He made his final appearance for Italy under [[Marcello Lippi]], in an international friendly match against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] on 9 February 2005, held in Cagliari, which Italy won 2–0.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/nazionale/2005/02/italiarussia.shtml |title=L'Italia vola con il tridente-bis |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=it |date=9 February 2005 |access-date=3 October 2018 }}</ref> In total, Montella won twenty caps and scored three goals for Italy.<ref name="figc">{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=1241&squadra=1|title=Nazionale in cifre: Montella, Vincenzo|website=figc.it|publisher=FIGC|language=it|access-date=22 April 2015|archive-date=20 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520120936/http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=1241&squadra=1|url-status=dead}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Nicknamed "''L'Aeroplanino''" ("The Little Airplane"), due to his small stature and trademark [[goal celebration]], in which he spread his arms like wings, Montella was known as a quick, hard-working, intelligent and opportunistic left-footed [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]], who was gifted with pace, good technique and a keen eye for goal, and was capable of striking the ball well with either foot; he has also been described as a "fine all round player, with excellent passing and [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] skills." Although he was primarily played as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre-forward]], a position in which he earned a reputation as a prolific "goal-poacher", his wide range of skills made him a versatile [[Forward (association football)|forward]], who also capable of playing in a more creative role as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second striker]]. However, despite his ability and goalscoring record as a footballer, at times he was criticised by his Roma manager Fabio Capello for being a "selfish" player; he was also known to be injury-prone.<ref name="Montella comes to the fore"/><ref name="Euro 2000"/><ref name="UEFA"/><ref name="ritorno"/><ref name="espn"/><ref name="treccani2">{{cite web|url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/vincenzo-montella/|title=MONTELLA, Vincenzo|publisher=Treccani: Enciclopedia dello Sport (2002)|language=it|author=Enrico Maida|access-date=3 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.espn.com/soccer/story?storyId=257738&lang=EN&wjb=&pg=1|title=Roma - Squad profiles|publisher=ESPN|date=13 February 2003|access-date=22 February 2017|archive-date=4 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201104100728/http://m.espn.com/soccer/story?storyId=257738&lang=EN&wjb=&pg=1|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="treccani1">{{cite web|url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/vincenzo-montella/|title=Montella, Vincenzo|publisher=Treccani: Enciclopedie on line|language=it|access-date=3 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pianetamilan.it/rassegna/berlusconi-tutto-il-mondo-gli-ha-fatto-gli-auguri/|title=Berlusconi, tutto il mondo gli ha fatto gli auguri|publisher=PianetaMilan.it|language=it|author1=Stefano Bressi|date=30 September 2016|access-date=23 March 2017|archive-date=3 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181003220930/http://www.pianetamilan.it/rassegna/berlusconi-tutto-il-mondo-gli-ha-fatto-gli-auguri/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="tuttocalciatori">{{cite web |url=https://www.tuttocalciatori.net/montella%20vincenzo |title=Montella, Vincenzo |publisher=www.tuttocalciatori.net |language=it |access-date=3 October 2018 }}</ref> During the 1999–2000 season former Italy striker [[Paolo Rossi]] likened Montella's playing style to his own, commenting "He's the striker who most reminds me of myself,."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asroma.com/en/news/61632/history-makers-vincenzo-montella |title=History Makers: Vincenzo Montella |publisher=AS Roma |language=en |date=18 June 2021 |access-date=2 May 2024 }}</ref>

==Coaching career==
===Roma===
[[File:Vincenzo Montella.JPG|thumb|right|Montella as Roma coach, 2011]]
Montella signed a three-year contract with Roma as youth team coach for the ''Giovanissimi Nazionali'' (under-15 level).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asroma.it/pdf/corporate/operazioni_di_mercato/2009-07-02_accordo_per_la_risoluzione_consensuale_anticipata_del_contratto_economico_per_le_prestazioni_sportive_del_calciatore_vincenzo_montella.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608035655/http://www.asroma.it/pdf/corporate/operazioni_di_mercato/2009-07-02_accordo_per_la_risoluzione_consensuale_anticipata_del_contratto_economico_per_le_prestazioni_sportive_del_calciatore_vincenzo_montella.pdf|title=AS Roma-Vincenzo Montella |date=2 July 2009 |access-date=1 September 2016 |publisher=AS Roma |language=it |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 June 2012 }}</ref>

On 21 February 2011, he was appointed as interim head coach of the first team for the remainder of the season, taking over the role from resigning boss [[Claudio Ranieri]].<ref name="montella_coach">{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/roma/2011/02/21/news/vertice_roma_per_futuro-12712599/?ref=HRERO-1 |title=La Roma ha scelto Panchina a Montella |work=La Repubblica |language=it |date=21 February 2011 |access-date=21 February 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Roma/21-02-2011/a-trigoria-si-decide-futuro-80233152494.shtml|title=Montella scuote la Roma "Ascolto, ma poi scelgo io"|work=gazzetta.it|language=it|date=21 February 2011|access-date=21 February 2011}}</ref> On 23 February, in his first Serie A match in charge, Roma won away against [[Bologna FC 1909|Bologna]], 1–0.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Bologna/23-02-2011/prima-gioia-montella-80261648206.shtml|title=Prima gioia per Montella, De Rossi abbatte il Bologna|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=it|date=23 February 2011|access-date=13 October 2011}}</ref> On 8 March, in his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] managerial debut, Roma lost away to [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]], 3–0.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iltempo.it/sport/2011/03/11/roma-fuori-di-testa-1.91516|title=Roma fuori di testa|work=Il Tempo|language=it|date=11 March 2011|access-date=17 December 2015|archive-date=10 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110070653/http://www.iltempo.it/sport/2011/03/11/roma-fuori-di-testa-1.91516|url-status=dead}}.</ref> Montella completed an eventful season for Roma, leading the ''Giallorossi'' to sixth place in the league table, and he was subsequently released, after the new club owners led by American businessman [[Thomas R. DiBenedetto]] decided to appoint [[Luis Enrique]] as permanent head coach for the [[2011–12 AS Roma season|2011–12 season]].

===Catania===
On 9 June 2011, and only a few days after being released by Roma, Montella was announced as new boss of [[Calcio Catania|Catania]], signing a two-year contract with the Eastern Sicilian club.<ref name="montella_catania">{{cite news|url=http://www.calciocatania.it/comunicati/comunicati.php?id=23140|archive-url=https://archive.today/20110727110006/http://www.calciocatania.it/comunicati/comunicati.php?id=23140|archive-date=27 July 2011|title=Vincenzo Montella è il nuovo allenatore del Catania – Venerdì 10 giugno alle 16.30 la presentazione|publisher=Calcio Catania|date=9 June 2011|access-date=4 December 2013|language=it|url-status=dead}}</ref> He led Catania to a mid-table placement, and ahead of Sicilian rivals [[US Città di Palermo|Palermo]] for the first time in eight years; by the end of season, he was heavily linked with a comeback at Roma and the vacant job at Fiorentina. Montella left Catania by mutual consent on 4 June 2012, after only one season in charge.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.calciocatania.it/allenamenti/allenamenti.php?id=26494|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120804052707/http://www.calciocatania.it/allenamenti/allenamenti.php?id=26494|archive-date=4 August 2012|title=Vincenzo Montella: 'Grazie, Catania|trans-title=Vincenzo Montella: 'Thanks, Catania'|publisher=Calcio Catania|language=it|date=4 June 2012|access-date=4 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Fiorentina===
[[File:Vincenzo montella.JPG|thumb|right|Montella as Fiorentina head coach, 2012]]
On 11 June 2012, Fiorentina announced on their official website that Montella signed a two-year deal (later extended until June 2017) with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballcracy.com/news/serie-a/vincenzo-montella-is-the-new-fiorentina-coach/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130123104700/http://www.footballcracy.com/news/serie-a/vincenzo-montella-is-the-new-fiorentina-coach/|archive-date=23 January 2013|title=Vincenzo Montella is the new Fiorentina coach|publisher=Footballcracy|date=11 June 2012|access-date=4 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Montella's arrival saw a massive upheaval of the squad, which saw 17 (including [[Borja Valero]] and [[Alberto Aquilani]]) out of the 26 senior players being new to the club. Fiorentina finished the [[2012–13 Serie A]] in fourth place, missing out on a Champions League spot to [[AC Milan|Milan]] on the final day of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/may/20/italy-siena-penalty-milan-champions-league|title=Italy cries foul over penalty that helped Milan into Champions League|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 May 2013|access-date=3 May 2014}}</ref>

In his second season in charge, Montella led Fiorentina to the [[2014 Coppa Italia Final|2014 Coppa Italia final]], but were beaten 3–1 by [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27271913|title=Coppa Italia final: Rafael Benitez's Napoli beat Fiorentina 3-1|work=BBC Sport|date=3 May 2014|access-date=3 May 2014}}</ref> while the team finished the [[2013–14 Serie A|league season]] in fourth place once again. In his third season, Montella helped Fiorentina reach the semi-final of the [[2014–15 UEFA Europa League]], where they were eliminated by defending champions and eventual winners [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]. Fiorentina finished the [[2014–15 Serie A|league season]] in fourth place for the third consecutive season. On 8 June, he was sacked.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/33057869|title=Vincenzo Montella sacked as Fiorentina head coach|publisher=BBC|date=8 June 2015|access-date=8 June 2015}}</ref>

===Sampdoria===
On 15 November 2015, Sampdoria announced Montella as their new head coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-italia.net/75789/sampdoria-announce-montella|title=Sampdoria announce Montella|work=Football Italia|date=15 November 2015|access-date=17 December 2015}}</ref> On 28 June 2016, Montella left the club to join Milan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/86555/montella-%E2%80%98thank-you-sampdoria%E2%80%99|title=Montella: 'Thank you, Sampdoria' - Football Italia|website=www.football-italia.net}}</ref>

===Milan===
On 28 June 2016, Milan announced Montella as their new head coach, with a contract starting from 1 July. He signed a two-year deal, reportedly worth €2.3&nbsp;million per year, while Sampdoria were paid €500,000 as a compensation to release him from his contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/it/news/show/162262|title=AC MILAN MONTELLA BROCCHI {{!}} News|access-date=28 June 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629102503/http://www.acmilan.com/it/news/show/162262|archive-date=29 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calciomercato/28-06-2016/montella-milan-accordo-un-biennale-23-milioni-160150328556.shtml|title=Milan: "Montella, benvenuto". Firma un biennale da 2,3 milioni|access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> On 23 December, Montella led the "Rossoneri" to their first title since 2011, the [[2016 Supercoppa Italiana|Supercoppa Italiana]], defeating Juventus 4–3 in a penalty shootout, after a 1–1 draw following extra time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/96104/milan-beat-juve-super-cup-shoot-out|title=Milan beat Juve in Super Cup shoot-out|publisher=Football Italia|date=23 December 2016|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/ac-milan/103/blog/post/3025757/milan-beat-juventus-in-italian-super-cup-as-gianluigi-donnarumma-and-suso-stood-out|title=Milan beat Juventus in Super Cup as Donnarumma, Suso lead the charge|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Sumeet Paul|date=23 December 2016|access-date=24 December 2016}}</ref> With a sixth-place finish in the [[2016–17 Serie A|league his first season]], Montella led Milan to qualify for the third round of [[2017–18 UEFA Europa League]] qualification phase, marking Milan's return to European competition for the first time since February 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/ac-milan/103/blog/post/3133485/getting-back-to-europe-should-be-seen-as-a-big-achievement-for-ac-milan|title=Getting back to Europe should be seen as a big achievement for AC Milan {{!}} News|publisher=ESPN FC|author=Sumeet Paul|date=24 May 2017|access-date=20 August 2017}}</ref> On 30 May 2017, he signed a new contract until 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/official-statement/2017-05-30/montella-and-ac-milan-together-through-to-2019|title=MONTELLA AND AC MILAN TOGETHER THROUGH TO 2019|access-date=26 September 2017}}</ref>

Although much was expected of Milan after a €200m summer transfer campaign financed by the team's new owners, the first half of the [[2017–18 AC Milan season|2017–18 season]] was disappointing for the club; Montella drew criticism in the media for struggling to find a suitable formation for his players and a fixed starting eleven, and only won six out of the first 14 games in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/ac-milan-regret-bonucci-signing-72268|title=AC Milan regret Bonucci signing|publisher=www.calciomercato.com|date=1 October 2017|access-date=11 January 2018|archive-date=17 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717124750/https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/ac-milan-regret-bonucci-signing-72268|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/nima-tavallaey-where-do-ac-milan-go-from-here-98188|title=Where do AC Milan go from here?|publisher=www.calciomercato.com|author1=Nima Tavallaey Roodsari|date=30 October 2017|access-date=11 January 2018|archive-date=17 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717124852/https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/nima-tavallaey-where-do-ac-milan-go-from-here-98188|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/113495/milan-problems-beyond-montella|title=Milan problems beyond Montella|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Gaby McKay|date=28 November 2017|access-date=11 January 2018}}</ref> Following these poor results at the beginning of the [[2017–18 Serie A]] season, Montella was eventually sacked by Milan on 27 November 2017, following a 0–0 home draw against [[Torino FC|Torino]] the day before;<ref name="Vincenzo Montella leaves AC Milan; Gennaro Gattuso placed in charge">{{cite news|title=Vincenzo Montella leaves AC Milan; Gennaro Gattuso placed in charge|url=http://www.espnfc.us/ac-milan/story/3286710/vincenzo-montella-leaves-ac-milan;-gennaro-gattuso-placed-in-charge|access-date=27 November 2017|work=ESPN FC|publisher=ESPN|date=27 November 2017}}</ref> [[Gennaro Gattuso]] was announced as Montella's replacement.<ref name="Vincenzo Montella leaves AC Milan; Gennaro Gattuso placed in charge"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42136435|title=Vincenzo Montella: AC Milan sack coach & place Gennaro Gattuso in charge|work=BBC Sport|date=27 November 2017|access-date=28 November 2017}}</ref>

===Sevilla===
On 28 December 2017, Spanish club [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] announced the appointment of Montella as the replacement of the recently sacked [[Eduardo Berizzo]], signing a contract which would last until mid-2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2017/12/28/football/1514472981_757896.html |title=Montella signs as Sevilla coach to 2019 |publisher=AS |author1=José María López |date=28 December 2017 |access-date=3 October 2018 }}</ref>

During his tenure, Montella managed to guide Sevilla to a first-ever Champions League quarter-final, defeating [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 2–1 on aggregate in the round of 16.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43376849 |title=Manchester United 1-2 Sevilla |work=BBC Sport |author1=Shamoon Hafez |date=13 March 2018 |access-date=3 October 2018 }}</ref> Sevilla were beaten by [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in the quarter-finals 2–1 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2018/apr/11/bayern-munich-sevilla-champions-league-quarter-final-live |title=Bayern Munich 0-0 Sevilla (agg: 2-1) |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Rob Smyth |date=11 April 2018 |access-date=3 October 2018 }}</ref> Montella also led Sevilla to the 2018 [[Copa del Rey]] [[2018 Copa del Rey Final|final]], defeating teams such as [[Atlético Madrid]] and [[CD Leganés|Léganes]] in the process,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/spanish-primera-division/15/blog/post/3377302/sevilla-return-to-copa-del-rey-final-boost-of-confidence-amid-difficult-season |title=Sevilla return to Copa del Rey final, a tonic amid a difficult season |publisher=ESPN FC |author1=Sid Lowe |date=9 February 2018 |access-date=3 October 2018 }}</ref> though they suffered a 5–0 defeat to [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref name="2018CdR">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43845692 |title=Sevilla 0–5 Barcelona |website=[[BBC Sport]] |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=21 April 2018 |access-date=21 April 2018}}</ref>

Despite being the finalists of the [[Copa del Rey|Copa Del Rey]], [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] struggled with their league form, and on 28 April 2018, Montella was sacked, following a run of nine games without a victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-au/amp/news/vincenzo-montella-sacked-by-struggling-sevilla/1x3kdv9tuq04w1uhb330cijtfb|title=Vincenzo Montella sacked by struggling Sevilla|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal.com]]|date=28 April 2018|access-date=28 April 2018|archive-date=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013023545/http://www.goal.com/en-au/amp/news/vincenzo-montella-sacked-by-struggling-sevilla/1x3kdv9tuq04w1uhb330cijtfb|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Return to Fiorentina===
On 10 April 2019, Montella returned to [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] after the resignation of [[Stefano Pioli]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/136830/official-montella-returns-fiorentina|title=OFFICIAL: Montella returns to Fiorentina|publisher=Football Italia|date=10 April 2019}}</ref> Following a 1–4 away defeat to [[AS Roma|Roma]] in Serie A on 20 December 2019, he was dismissed from his managerial post the day after.<ref>{{cite news |title=Montella sacked as Fiorentina boss after Roma defeat |url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/montella-sacked-as-fiorentina-boss-after-roma-defeat |website=[[The World Game]] |date=21 December 2019 |access-date=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Fiorentina fires coach Montella after Roma defeat |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/12/21/fiorentina-fires-coach-montella-after-roma-defeat/40867763/ |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=21 December 2019 |access-date=22 December 2019}}</ref>

===Adana Demirspor===
On 1 September 2021, Montella signed a two-year contract with [[Adana Demirspor]], starting off on a new experience for himself in [[Turkey]].<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=AdsKulubu |number=1433069702985789443 |title=Kulübümüz daha önce Fiorentina, Sevilla, Milan, Sampdoria ve Roma takımlarını çalıştıran teknik direktör Vincenzo Montella ile 2 yıllık anlaşma imzalamıştır.|language=tr}}</ref> In his [[2021–22 Adana Demirspor season|first season]], Adana Demirspor finished ninth in the league.

In his [[2022–23 Adana Demirspor season|second season]], Adana Demirspor finished the league in fourth place with a record of 20 wins, nine draws and seven losses in 36 matches, which was their best league position in their history that qualified them to first participation ever in European competitions, namely the [[2023–24 UEFA Europa Conference League|Conference League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/european-journey-of-turkish-football-clubs-in-new-season/2923583 |title=European journey of Turkish football clubs in new season |publisher=Anadolu Agency |date=15 June 2023 }}</ref>

On 12 June 2023, Adana Demirspor announced that they had parted ways with Montella by mutual consent at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=AdsKulubu |number=1668330441944727565 |title=HER ŞEY İÇİN TEŞEKKÜRLER💙|language=tr}}</ref>

===Turkey===
On 21 September 2023, Montella was unveiled as the new manager of the [[Turkey national football team]], a day after [[Stefan Kuntz]] was sacked following a 4&minus;2 friendly loss against [[Japan national football team|Japan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tff.org/default.aspx?pageID=687&ftxtID=42209 |publisher=Turkish Football Federation |language=tr |title=A Milli Futbol Takımımızın Yeni Teknik Direktörü Vincenzo Montella |date=21 September 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Sabah |first=Daily |date=17 September 2023 |title=Türkiye sack national team coach Kuntz after underwhelming stint |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/sports/football/turkiye-sack-national-team-coach-kuntz-after-underwhelming-stint |access-date=17 September 2023 |website=Daily Sabah |language=en-US}}</ref>

On 12 October 2023, Montella managed his first official match in a 0–1 away victory to [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/655392/turkey-croatia |title=Turkey 1-0 Croatia (Oct 12, 2023) Final Score |publisher=ESPN |access-date=18 June 2024 }}</ref> On 15 October 2023, he qualified the national team for [[UEFA Euro 2024]] after a 4–0 win over [[Latvia national football team|Latvia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20231015-spain-scotland-and-turkey-lock-up-euro-2024-spots |title=Spain, Scotland and Turkey lock up Euro 2024 spots |work=France 24 |date=15 October 2023 |access-date=18 June 2024 }}</ref> In the opening match of the final tournament, Turkey defeated [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]] 3–1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/turkey-georgia-euro-2024-live-stream-score-result-b2563764.html |title=Turkey vs Georgia LIVE: Euro 2024 result and reaction after Arda Guler wonder goal |work=The Independent |last1=Wilson |first1=Chris |date=17 June 2024 |access-date=18 June 2024 }}</ref> Turkey lost their second match 3–0 to [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], but won their final group match against [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] 2–1, advancing to the second round in second place in their group with six points.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/40348445/euro-2024-every-team-needs-go-group-stage |title=Euro 2024: How every team qualified from the group stage |work=ESPN.com |language=en |date=26 June 2024 |access-date=5 July 2024 }}</ref> In the round of 16, Turkey defeated [[Austria national football team|Austria]] 2–1 to advance to the quarter-finals of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2024/07/02/sport/austria-turkey-last-16-euro-2024-spt-intl/index.html |title=Merih Demiral scores twice as Turkey advances to Euro 2024 quarterfinals with victory over Austria in frenzied atmosphere |work=CNN |last1=Morse |first1=Ben |language=en |date=2 July 2024 |access-date=5 July 2024 }}</ref> Turkey were eliminated from the tournament in the quarter-finals following a 2–1 defeat to [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jul/06/netherlands-turkey-euro-2024-match-report |title=Netherlands fight back to see off Turkey and set up semi-final against England |work=The Observer |last1=Ames |first1=Nick |date=6 July 2024 |access-date=7 July 2024 }}</ref> In Montella’s coaching, Turkey managed to both advance from the group stage and reach the quarterfinals in an international tournament for the first time in 16 years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sarigul |first1=E. |title=Montella reaps rewards of embracing Turkey’s fan culture pandemonium |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jul/05/euro-2024-turkey-vincenzo-montella-arda-guler-merih-demiral-preview |website=The Guardian |access-date=31 March 2026 |date=5 July 2024}}</ref>

Following this tournament, Montella remained in charge of the Turkish national team as they finished second in [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League B|League B]] of the [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League]], competing alongside [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]], [[Montenegro national football team|Montenegro]], and [[Wales national football team|Wales]]. A 3–1 defeat to Montenegro in their final match saw them finish behind Wales in the group.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/sports/wales-promoted-to-nations-league-a-after-turkiye-stunned-at-montenegro/3398405 |title=Wales promoted to Nations League A after Türkiye stunned at Montenegro |publisher=Anadolu Ajansı |date=20 November 2024 }}</ref> In the promotion play-offs against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] in March 2025, Turkey secured a 6–1 aggregate victory (3–1 and 3–0), earning promotion to [[2026–27 UEFA Nations League A|League A]] for the first time and their first win over Hungary in 18 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/sports/football/turkiye-storm-into-uefa-nations-league-a-with-3-0-win-over-hungary |title=Türkiye storm into UEFA Nations League A with 3-0 win over Hungary |publisher=Daily Sabah |date=23 March 2025 }}</ref>

In the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification|2026 World Cup qualifiers]], Turkey finished second in [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group E|their group]] behind [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and proceeded to [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA second round|the play-offs]]. They then defeated [[Romania national football team|Romania]] 1–0 in the play-off semi-finals on 26 March 2026, advancing to face [[Kosovo national football team|Kosovo]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web |title=We Are Just One Step Away From the World Cup! |url=https://www.tff.org/default.aspx?pageID=471&ftxtID=50071 |website=tff.org |access-date=31 March 2026 |date=26 March 2026}}</ref> Five days later, on 31 March, Turkey defeated Kosovo 1–0 in the play-off final, securing qualification for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], their first appearance since 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/turkey-end-24-year-world-cup-drought-with-win-over-kosovo-2026-03-31/ |title=Turkey end 24-year World Cup drought with win over Kosovo |publisher=Reuters |date=31 March 2026 }}</ref>

==Media==
Montella has featured in [[EA Sports]]' [[FIFA (video game series)|''FIFA'' video game series]]; he was on the cover for the Italian edition of ''[[FIFA 2000]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.ign.com/fifa-14-playstation-3/67594/feature/fifa-storie-di-copertina|title=FIFA: storie di copertina|website=ign.com|language=it|author1=Mattia Ravanelli|date=7 September 2013|access-date=17 March 2015}}</ref>

